Explanation: `__eq__` uses `is`, so objects are equal only when they are the same object (same identity). `__hash__` returns `id(self)`, which is stable for the object’s lifetime and unique among live objects, so the hash is consistent with identity-based equality: if `a is b` then `id(a) == id(b)` and thus their hashes match. If `a is not b`, they should not compare equal, and their hashes will typically differ (collisions are allowed but rare). This makes the class safe and predictable as a `dict` key or `set` element under identity semantics.

